#PressPlay: Get y’all popcorn ready, Chance the Rapper’s new movie drops today in theaters across the country! “Chance the Rapper’s Magnificent Coloring World” marks the first time an artist has independently distributed a film to theatres.
________
“Magnificent Coloring World” is a concert film self-distributed through Chance the Rapper’s House of Kicks production company and film house.
________
Chance wrote, produced, edited and starred in the film, working hard this past year to bring never-before-seen footage to his fans. The footage was filmed in 2017 right before Chance took home 3 Grammys for his critically acclaimed mixtape “Coloring Book.”
________
Fans will be able to see the film in person for a limited time in several cities including Los Angeles, New York, Chicago, Detori, Las Vegas and Philly.

node.title: Chance The Rapper’s Film Released Today

node.text:
TSR STAFF: Danielle J!
@prettyaries16
______________________
�#Roommates, last summer multiple companies and organizations pledged to step up and do their part to put racial equality and diversity at the forefront—and one of those organizations was the #NFL. In an effort to stand firm on its promise, the NFL recently announced that before every game of the 2021 season, the Black national anthem, “Lift Ev’ry Voice And Sing,” will be played.
______________________
@NYTimes reports, as part of its 10-year, $250 million pledge to help fight racism in America, the NFL has decided to play “Lift Ev’ry Voice And Sing” (also known as the Black national anthem) before every NFL game this season, including playoff games. In the recent season opener earlier this month, NFL players stood with their arms locked together, while Alicia Keys and Florida A&M’s choir performed the song.
_____________________
Additionally, not only will “Lift Ev’ry” Voice And Sing” be played at games, but players will also be allowed to wear decals on their helmets with one of six pre-approved messages regarding social justice. Meanwhile, the NFL will continue to display the slogans “It Takes All of Us” and “End Racism” on end zones as a continued sign of solidarity with movements to combat racism and police brutality.
